            <h4 class="text-center text-danger">Fag el-Gamous translates to "Way of the Water Buffalo." </h4>
            <p>
                The Fag el-Gamous ancient burial site is located on the eastern edge of the Fayoum Depression, approximately 55 miles (90 km) south of Cairo, Egypt.
                During multiple years of study, researchers have excavated more than 1,000 mummies that have provided a plethora of knowledge and understanding about ancient cultures.
                This site has yielded vast amounts of archaeological evidence that the researchers at BYU want to make available to the public, as they believe that the data is beneficial to many scholars around the world.
            </p>
           
            <br />
            <p>
                This ancient burial site has been under archeological investigation (primarily by Brigham Young University researchers) for over 25 years.
                This Graeco-Roman cemetery is one that also includes a Graeco-Roman township,
                some Middle Kingdom tombs, and a small Old Kingdom pyramid that dates to Pharaoh Snefru (circa 2613–2589 BCE; Dynasty IV).
                The majority of BYU's excavation efforts since 1996 have been concentrated in the Graeco-Roman cemetery.
            </p>
