            <h4 class="text-center text-danger">BYU Egypt Excavation Project </h4>
            <p>
                Thanks to the efforts of Brigham Young University students and faculty, <b>the archaelogical data from the Fag el-Gamous burial site has been made available to the public.</b>
                Click <a asp-action="BurialRecords"> <i>here</i> </a> to see the complete record of the excavations from the Fag el-Gamous site. <br />
            </p>

            <p>
                Since the excavation began at Fag el-Gamous, BYU researchers have been collecting the data in field notes, spreadsheets, and simple databases to record different information about each dig.
                Information about the location of the dig, the physical orientation of the body in the ground, burial depth, hair color, textile wrapping, gender, age, bone dimensions, items accompanying the mummy,
                and much more has been recorded for each burial site found. Offsite researchers have performed a variety of different analyses on excavated materials including carbon dating and DNA sequencing.
                <b>Now that the data has been moved to an online platform, anyone in the world can access the burial records from Fag el-Gamous</b>

            </p>
            <br />
            <p>
                To begin to understand how each the dig record is uniquely identified, we first need to understand how the Fag el-Gamous excavation site is split up. The site is organized using a grid system where a square is defined by the coordinate North,
                South, East, or West from a single origin point. Each square of the grid system is then subdivided into the Northwest, Northeast, Southeast, or Southwest quadrants within the grid square (i.e. each grid “square” within the grid system is further
                divided into 4 smaller parts called “quadrants” to keep accurate location records for each record). Because many mummies (usually 40 or more) are found in each grid square, a number is assigned (eg. #9) to uniquely identify each burial that is found within each grid
                square.
            </p>
            <br />
            <p>

                Each dig record is currently identified by a composite key called Burial_Id. This composite key consists of the coordinates (N, S, E, or W) of an origin, combined with the quadrant (NW, NE, SE, or SW) within the grid square. Lastly, a number is assigned to each burial
                within a square and quadrant pairing. An example burial location is “N 190/200 E 40/50 SE #9.”

            </p>
            <br />
            <p>
                Users should be aware that each dig record may not contain the same types of information. For example, where the gender may be available for one record, the gender may not be identifiable in another. In short, every field entry of the database (excluding the key and location fields) can be null.
                This does not indicate that the dig record is incorrect or incomplete; rather a missing field indicates that the information was not available to the researchers or is still under investigation.

            </p>


